body:
Although the error here is "Unsupported in C", it's a similar case to #599, which is fixed, so it may be that this is intended to work but the fix for #599 just didn't handle the enum case.

```
package pack;
  typedef enum logic[0:0] { P = 1'b0 } e_t;
endpackage

module a
import pack::*;
();
  localparam P = 1;
endmodule
```
output:
```
%Error: a.sv:8:14: Unsupported in C: Variable has same name as ENUMITEM 'P': 'P'
    8 |   localparam P = 1;
      |              ^
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
        ... See the manual at https://verilator.org/verilator_doc.html for more assistance.
```
SystemVerilog standard says pack::P is "potentially locally visible" in a, and it ends up not being visible since P is locally declared in a. Seems like once Verilator front end has resolved the scope, it does not need to generate C code for pack::P in a at all, so there should be no clash of names in the C code - but even if it had to somehow reference both pack::P and the localparam, it could achieve that by mangling the names somehow.
